pushed it open. Initially he thought she had fallen. He then saw his mother lying flat on her face, completely still, with a very significant pool of blood coming from her head or face.</p><p>\"He saw that her trousers had been pulled down slightly and that on the back of her head there was a significant pinkish dent, as if caused by one huge hit or by several blows in the same place. It was obvious to him that she was dead and that she had been murdered.\"</p><p>Bowes told the jury that Mrs Edmonds had suffered about 30 knife wounds. The prosecution claims a paring knife was used to jab the pensioner, \"part of escalating violence in order to get information out of her\". Each wound was \"very deliberate\", Bowes said. The knife was also dragged across the victim's throat, leaving a deep gash.</p><p>\"The many knife wounds penetrated Georgina Edmonds's skin. Their pattern suggests they had been inflicted with some deliberation rather than a significant degree of force,\" said Bowes. \"Given the theft of her credit card and its unsuccessful use hours later, the inference is she was tortured in order to obtain her pin and then beaten to death.\"</p><p>Bowes claimed Hamlen had walked in through an unlocked back door and made his escape via a towpath near the cottage.</p><p>He said Mrs Edmonds's credit card, mobile phone and handbag were stolen. At 10.38pm on the same day, someone tried unsuccessfully to use her credit card at a cash machine outside Tesco Express in Eastleigh. The person who used the card tried to hide his identity under the hood of a fluorescent jacket. The prosecution alleges this was Hamlen.</p><p>Hamlen told police he walked in the area where the cottage was. He said he might have gone into the grounds of the cottage because he liked old houses and castles and enjoyed \"a nose\".</p><p>\"He could not remember climbing over the five bar gate to the drive but said he did do things like that,\" said Bowes.</p><p>Hamlen told detectives he had a £100-a-